                methodologyTurnoverTitle:      '6. Turnover Cost Model',
                methodologyTurnoverAssumptions:'Uses your actual Team Size and Blended Rate (Q6) multiplied by 1,800 annual hours (aligned with ANNUAL_HOURS_PER_ENGINEER across the model). The $150/hr and 50-engineer defaults are no longer hardcoded — the model reads your diagnostic inputs in real time.',
                methodologyTurnoverSource:     'SHRM Foundation — "Retaining Talent: A Guide to Analyzing and Managing Employee Turnover" (2025 update). SHRM 2025 Benchmarking Reports, shrm.org/benchmarking.',
                methodologyDoraTitle:          '7. DORA Benchmark Thresholds',
                methodologyDoraBody:           'The four software delivery performance clusters (Elite, High, Medium, Low) correspond to the 2024 Accelerate State of DevOps Report published by Google Cloud\'s DORA team. Lead time thresholds: Elite <1 day, High 1 day–1 week, Medium 1 week–1 month, Low >1 month. Deployment frequency: Elite On-demand, High daily–weekly, Medium weekly–monthly, Low monthly–biannually. Note: DORA\'s four official metrics are Deployment Frequency, Lead Time for Changes, Change Failure Rate, and Failed Deployment Recovery Time. The manual-effort and human-error mappings in this tool are an adaptation, not official DORA categories.',
                methodologyDoraSource:         'Google Cloud DORA — Accelerate State of DevOps Report 2024. dora.dev/research/2024/dora-report/',
                methodologyFxTitle:            '8. Exchange Rates',
                methodologyFxBody:             'Live mid rates are fetched from Narodowy Bank Polski (NBP) Table A via api.nbp.pl on page load. Fallback rates if the API is unavailable: 1 USD = 0.87 EUR / 3.67 PLN / 0.75 GBP.',
                methodologyFxSource:         'Narodowy Bank Polski — Table A mid exchange rates. api.nbp.pl.',
                methodologyTotalTitle:       '9. Total Debt Impact',
                methodologyTotalFormula:     'OPEX Waste + Risk Exposure + Pipeline Margin Erosion + OPEX-adjusted Estimate',
                methodologyTotalNote:        'Pipeline Margin Erosion (cOppDirect) is a one-time estimate reflecting margin lost in the first year of delay. All other components recur annually. The OPEX-adjusted Estimate is proportional to OPEX Waste — reducing manual waste automatically reduces this component.',
                methodologyTotalSource:      'Economic model synthesised from BLS ATUS (2024), OECD Annual Hours (2024), Exepron "True Cost of Delay" (2026), COSO ERM (2017), and SHRM Retention Framework (2025).',
                methodologyNpvTitle:         '10. NPV & IRR Economic Model',
                methodologyNpvFormula:       'NPV = One-Time Costs + PVIFA × Annual Recurring | IRR = rate where Σ(CFₜ/(1+r)^(t/12)) = 0',
                methodologyNpvNote:          'One-time costs = Pipeline Margin Erosion + CAPEX. Annual recurring = OPEX Waste + Risk + OPEX-adjusted Estimate. PVIFA discounts the recurring stream using a 10% WACC over a 5-year horizon. Discounted Payback uses monthly DCF to find the break-even month. IRR (Internal Rate of Return) is computed via binary search over monthly cash flows — the rate at which NPV = 0. IRR > WACC (10%) indicates value creation. This aligns with standard capital budgeting (Brealey, Myers & Allen) and COSO ERM 2017 guidance on multi-period risk assessment.',
                methodologyNpvSource:        'Brealey, R.A., Myers, S.C. & Allen, F. — Principles of Corporate Finance (14th ed., McGraw-Hill). COSO — Enterprise Risk Management — Integrating with Strategy and Performance (2017). WACC benchmark: Damodaran, A. — Cost of Capital by Sector (2025), IT infrastructure median ~9.3%.',
                methodologyAdvancedTitle:    '11. Configurable Advanced Parameters',
                methodologyAdvancedBody:     'Six parameters in the "Advanced Parameters" panel let you override default coefficients in real time: OPEX-adjusted Estimate (0.0–0.3), Pipeline Erosion Rate (0.0–1.0), WACC / Discount Rate (5–20%), NPV Time Horizon (3–10 years), Automation Lever Recovery (10–60%), and Risk Lever Recovery (20–80%). Changing any slider immediately recalculates all dependent metrics. Defaults are restored on page reload.',
                methodologyAdvancedSource:   'User-configurable — overrides the Economic Model defaults (Section 10) in real time.',
                methodologyCorrelationsTitle: '12. Cross-Variable Correlations',
                methodologyCorrelationsBody:  'Four causal links between diagnostic inputs, each with configurable strength: (1) Higher Manual Effort (Q1) increases Human Errors (Q5) — manual steps introduce mistakes. (2) Higher Manual Effort (Q1) increases Management Overhead (Q7) — manual processes require more chase-time. (3) Better Documentation Standard (Q3) decreases Management Overhead (Q7) — clear docs reduce coordination. (4) Lower Documentation (Q3) increases Manual Effort (Q1) — knowledge gaps force rework. Default multiplier = 0.3, adjustable in range 0–1. Disabled by default — enables only when the user checks "Cross-Variable Correlations" in Advanced tab.',
                methodologyCorrelationsSource: 'Design assumption based on common DevOps causal chains. Not empirically validated — use with awareness.',
                methodologyNonlinearTitle:    '13. Nonlinear Cost Model',
                methodologyNonlinearBody:     'Three non-linear adjustments applied when enabled: (1) Economies of scale — effective team size = actual team size ^ 0.9, meaning a 100-engineer team costs less than 10× a 10-engineer team. (2) Cascade threshold — a sigmoid function (2/(1+exp(-cWaste/0.5M)) − 1) scales the cascade multiplier up for high-waste organisations and down for low-waste ones, reflecting the idea that small manual inefficiencies have low cascade impact but large ones amplify non-linearly. (3) Diminishing automation returns — the effective automation level = 1 − (1 − target)^1.2, so the first 30% of automation yields more savings than the last 30%. Disabled by default.',
                methodologyNonlinearSource:   'Economies of scale: standard production function (Cobb-Douglas with α=0.9). Cascade sigmoid: original design assumption. Diminishing returns: common observation in process automation literature — initial quick wins taper off.',
                methodologyMcTitle:           '14. Monte Carlo Confidence Intervals',
                methodologyMcBody:            'When enabled, runs 1,000 iterations of the full model with perturbed inputs. Each input (except riskLevel which is discrete 1–5) is sampled from a triangular distribution centred on the user\'s value with ±15% spread. MTTR uses a log-normal distribution (Box-Muller transform) with ±25% spread, reflecting the heavy-tailed nature of incident recovery times. Outputs are reported as median with 90% confidence interval [p5, p95]. A seeded PRNG (LCG, seed=42) ensures reproducibility across sessions. Disabled by default.',
                methodologyMcSource:          'Standard Monte Carlo method (Metropolis & Ulam 1949). Box-Muller transform for log-normal MTTR. 90% CI is a common regulatory reporting standard (Basel II/III, Solvency II).',
